title: For Sale:  1945 svw MB Mauser K98 war bring back good collector's piece
postcontent:
I'm selling my 1945 svw MB Mauser K98.  If you do research on this rifle, or know your stuff, you know that these were some of the last ditch effort rifles produced by the Germans in WWII, and the factories where they were being made were eventually invaded by the French who took over production.  The French produced svw MB rifles are much more common.  This is a 100% German completed rifle.

Fires a 7.92x57mm round, also known as 8mm Mauser.  I have some FMJ and some soft point ammo I can include if the buyer wants to use this as a deer rifle for the season coming up!

The good:
The action and barrel are in fantastic shape.  The bore is a little dark, but it isn't pitted.  There is a very small amount of surface corrosion on the front sight.  I haven't cleaned any of this off because it is such a collector's piece.  This is an all-numbers matching rifle.  Every number checks out on every piece included.  Action is SMOOTH like the Mauser action is known to be!

The bad:
It was duffle cut by the soldier who brought it back and as such it is missing the top handguard for the stock, the front of the stock where both barrel bands would be, missing both barrel bands, a front sight hood, action screws, and the butt plate.  The stock has also been painted white, but that's because these rifles had to be sealed up before they were allowed to be shipped back.  The gun as is tells a great story.  However, a full kriegsmodell stock in red laminate would make this a nearly complete collectors piece, which has been quoted at and known to sell at auctions for upwards of $3,000.

This would make for a fantastic project for an avid collector.  I just don't fit that role and I know the soldier who brought it back would have liked to see it go to someone who can appreciate it more than I can.  Since it's only worth what someone is willing to pay, I'm only asking $600 cash.  I'm not interested in trades as I'm trying to get out from under this gun, and another gun would just put me in the same boat.

title: For Sale:  FBI SWAT Springfield Professional 1911
postcontent:
Barely used Springfield 1911 FBI Professional Custom Model in .45ACP This firearm has had only 200 to 300 rounds through it and has almost zero signs of wear. some history on the firearm: "This is the venerable Springfield Armory Professional Model. arguably the finest 1911 in the world. This particular variant of the 1911 is used by our elite military and law enforcement personnel. The Professional is most famous for it's use by the FBI's elite hostage rescue team…"HRT" for short. It is the most stringently tested 1911 in history and has been in constant production since approximately 1998. It has earned a reputation as a hard nosed, never let you down and sometimes, larger than life topic of how good it is or is not. "Ooohs" and "aaahs" are regularly heard from the 1911 crowd if one is out on display at a shop. The Professional models meet or exceed all specifications of the FBI SWAT contract, including the accuracy requirement of 1.5" or better at 25 yards with Remington Golden Saber ammunition. The civilian pistols and the FBI pistols are built at the same time, with the gunsmiths never knowing whether a civilian or FBI agent will be using the pistol. These pistols are built approx. every 45 days, with the FBI order being filled first and civilian orders getting all of the remaining from the production run. (Two Year waiting list or longer.) These pistols do not have front cocking serrations or full length guide rods because the FBI chose not to have these features on their pistols. (Front cocking serrations catch on clothing and full length guide rods require additional tools for dis assembly. The accuracy requirement, however, was yet another requirement that bordered on the impossible. This stipulated that the pistol fire three consecutive 10-shot groups no larger than 1.5 inches at 25 yards from a Ransom Rest using service ammunition. The pistol then had 20,000 rounds fired through it and was again tested for accuracy. No more than a 15% accuracy reduction was permitted. A single stoppage over 2,500 rounds disqualified a pistol from the competition. Several notable manufacturers of 1911 type pistols submitted bids and test pistols, but when the testing was completed, only Springfield’s candidate met the performance criteria and the rest, as the old saying goes, is history. Springfield originally designated all pistols built to the FBI standard “Bureau Model,” but the FBI protested, so the name was changed to Professional Model. All Professional Model pistols, whether for government issue or commercial sale, are identical and carry the serial number prefix “CRG.” Each pistol has every component fitted to the closest tolerances possible while maintaining reliability and accuracy.Only the best components are used to assemble the pistol, but is how Springfield’s Custom Shop builds each pistol that makes them special. When the shooter disassembles the pistol, he finds that each major component—barrel, barrel bushing, slide stop and slide—is numbered with the last three digits of the pistol’s serial number. None of these components will fit any other pistol.  

Gun includes 6 magazines, VZ Grips (white pictured) and original Springfield grips.

GUN IS PRICED WAY BELOW AVERAGE GOING PRICE ON GUNBROKER.COM ETC., SO 2000 IS NON-NEGOTIABLE.

Here's the story on these guns.  Picked up the BHP couple years back.   Finish was gone, but the mechanics (except the guide rod) and bore were great.  Took the finish down and re-finished with Lauer Duracoat - White and Tactical Black.  

At the time, I was thinking of winter varmint hunting, so I decided on a matching AR15.  Of course, the hunt never came and the AR15 became another unfired safe-queen.  Only defects are a little abrasion on the top of the stock from pulling the charging handle with the stock collapsed and a tiny mark from contact in the safe (gotta look hard to see any flaws).

I did carry the BHP for a little while.  Probably has 150 or so rounds down the pipe since the restore - who knows how many rounds before that.  Shot it a couple times in local practical pistol matches.  Accurate and reliable - it is a Browning.  It does show a touch of wear from carry/cleaning, but still looks great.

The BHP has a couple carry marks and the duracoat is worn a little on the slide rails internally.

Individually, they look a little strange.  Together they are an awesome pair.  Two of the greatest firearms of all time.

I'd like to get $1200 for the pair - a fair price for those guns with the finish and quality parts.  Might consider breaking them up if they don't sell as a pair.  Open to offers as well.

I will need to see NCDL and purchase/CCW permit.  I can't stomach the idea of some thug wandering around Asheville with one of my former weapons.  I don't mind presenting my ID and permit, no reason for a buyer not to do the same.  If you can't legally own one of these, don't ask me to sell it to you.  Cash only, please no BS.  Meetings at reasonable times and in public places only.

Thanks for looking!
